  "review_text": "With only five graded stories published in 1961, this first yearly wrap‑up is necessarily compact.&nbsp; The new <i>Fantastic Four</i> title dominates the landscape - accounting for nearly 85% of the weighted average - and the final tally for the year lands at [SPAN: severity=success; fontsize=large; fonttype=bold; text=6.70], which is a very strong opening statement for the Marvel Age.\n\nThe only real drag on the score came from the two <i>Tales to Astonish</i> mini‑features, which dipped below the upper‑mid‑grade territory the FF issues comfortably occupied.&nbsp; As you'll see once the monthly volume ramps up, most months settle somewhere between <b>5</b> and <b>6</b>, with the occasional spike or crater depending on how wild the bullpen was feeling.\n\n[SPAN: display=block; severity=info; fonttype=bold; text=How do I know this?]\n\nBecause, as of April 2026, I've already read through the end of 1969 and am now circling back to polish these early reviews as I prepare to launch this site publicly.&nbsp; Some of these first‑pass write‑ups needed a little archaeological dusting to bring them up to my current standards.\n\nA weighted average in the 5-6 range - especially in a month that might eventually contain a dozen or more graded stories - is nothing to sneeze at.&nbsp; It means there are genuine highlights (and, yes, lowlights) every month.&nbsp; Anything above a 4.0 (VG) qualifies as \"readable,\" and all five 1961 entries clear that bar.&nbsp; In fact, all three FF issues land above mid‑grade, which is a very encouraging start.\n\n<b>However....that being said...</b>\n[BR] I promised to talk about the <b>Trope Trifecta</b>, and 1961 delivers it in pure, unfiltered form.\n[DIVIDER]\n\n[SPAN: display=block; fontsize=large; fonttype=bold; text=The Trope Trifecta of Early Marvel]\n\nThe most common early‑Silver‑Age tropes - the ones that will become familiar companions throughout the 1960s - are already fully deployed here:\n[HANG] * <b>Monsters</b>\n[HANG] * <b>Alien Invasions</b>\n[HANG] * \"<b>I am your Master!&nbsp; You are my Slave!\"</b>\n\nThere are certainly others, but these three alone map almost perfectly onto <i>Fantastic Four</i> #1-3 (in <b>order</b> no less).&nbsp; It's as if Stan and Jack were still working off the old Atlas playbook, only gradually nudging the material toward something new.&nbsp; By the end of the year, you can <i>just</i> start to see the outlines of a different kind of comic taking shape.\n\nI'm willing to treat these early stumbles and genre holdovers as growing pains - the creators were still figuring out what this book (and this universe) wanted to be.&nbsp; I'll go lenient where appropriate, but I'll still call out the rough edges when they matter (as I did with [LINK:1961:FF_2|FF #2]).\n\nAll three FF issues remain more than readable and genuinely entertaining, each contributing something to the emerging dynamic of the team - especially the interpersonal tensions that will become a defining feature of the title.&nbsp; For now, it may actually be fair to say that this is indeed \"The Greatest Comic Magazine in the World!\"\n\nBut... getting back to the Trope Trifecta...\n\n[SPAN: display=block; fontsize=large; fonttype=bold; text=MONSTERS]\nMarvel's early monsters are a glorious holdover from the Atlas era --  towering, tantrum‑prone behemoths with names that sound like rejected IKEA shelving units (<i>Gorgo</i>, <i>Goom</i>, <i>Gorgoom</i>, etc.).&nbsp; They stomp around, roar about conquering humanity, and are inevitably defeated by something embarrassingly simple, like a rope, a trick, or even termites.&nbsp; They're less \"existential threat\" and more \"toddler with city‑crushing strength,\" and honestly, that's part of the charm.\n[BR]\n\n[SPAN: display=block; fontsize=large; fonttype=bold; text=ALIEN INVASIONS]\nIf there's one thing 1960s Marvel aliens love, it's Earth.&nbsp; They cross entire galaxies to get something they apparently can't find anywhere else:&nbsp; the plot convenience of landing in the one solar system with Reed Richards in it.&nbsp; These invaders arrive in waves, often on the same Tuesday, all convinced Earth is the perfect place to subjugate, steal something, test a weapon, or impersonate livestock.&nbsp; We scratch our heads and keep asking \"Wasn't there any place <i>closer</i> to home where you could get {fill in the blank}?\"&nbsp; ... but they keep coming ...\n[BR]\n\n[SPAN: display=block; fontsize=large; fonttype=bold; text= \"I AM YOUR MASTER!&nbsp; YOU ARE MY SLAVE!\"]\nThis is the Silver Age's favorite dramatic flourish - shouted by so many who just happen to wander into the script that day.&nbsp; It's the universal villain catchphrase.&nbsp; Early Marvel villains treat mind control like Bluetooth - unreliable, easily interrupted, and somehow always unpaired at the worst possible moment.&nbsp; If a 1961 antagonist isn't proclaiming their mastery over at least one of the heroes, check their pulse - they might not be a real Marvel villain.\n[BR]\n\n[BR]\n<b>So that's the Trope Trifecta in all its 1961 glory.&nbsp; </b>\n[BR] Monsters, aliens, and melodramatic tyrants - the holy trinity of early Marvel chaos.\n\nBut the training wheels come off in 1962.\n[BR] More books.\n[BR] More characters.\n[BR] More chances for brilliance... and more opportunities for affectionate mockery.\n\nOnward.\n\n\n[DEVNOTE: *** SUMMARY_BEGIN ***\n*** THIS MONTH ***5 graded stories over 5 issues...TOTAL WEIGHT: 4.41 grade character issue   weight 7.5   ff        FF #3   1.25 7.0   ff        FF #1   1.25 6.5   ff        FF #2   1.25 5.5   groot     TTA #13 0.33 4.5   ant       TTA #27 0.336.70*** LAST MONTH ***0 graded stories over 0 issues...TOTAL WEIGHT: 0 grade character issue weight0.00\n*** SUMMARY_END ***]",
  "letters_page": "[HANG0] * Introduction to the Fantastic Four, the Mole Man, Skrulls, Hank Pym, Miracle Man, and yes...even <i>Groot</i>.\n[DEVNOTE: *** INTRODUCTION_BEGIN ***\nGroot | villain | Milestone: (first)\nNotes | first | Leslie Evans\nBen Grimm | Milestone: (first)\nFantastic Four | Milestone: (first)\nJohnny Storm | Milestone: (first)\nMole Man | villain | Milestone: (first)\nReed Richards | Milestone: (first)\nSue Storm | Milestone: (first)\nSkrulls | villain | Milestone: (first)\nHank Pym | Milestone: (first)\nNotes | first | villain | Miracle Man\n*** INTRODUCTION_END ***]\n[DEVNOTE: *** HIGHLIGHTS_BEGIN ***]\n[HANG0] * Pre-Marvel civilization is saved from the alien wooden threat of Groot, from Planet X...by <b>termites</b>!&nbsp; (<i>Naturally</i>)\n[HANG0] * The FF's chaotic, property‑destroying race to headquarters - the moment Marvel's \"heroes who behave like humans\" truly arrives.\n[HANG0] * Two issues in, Marvel stops being Atlas, the Skrulls crash the party, and the universe suddenly gets a lot weirder.\n[HANG0] * Hank Pym shrinks himself, nearly dies, and concludes that science should probably stop doing that.&nbsp; A perfectly reasonable reaction, and therefore destined not to last.\n[HANG0] * The Human Torch quits the Fantastic Four, giving Marvel its first real cliffhanger!\n[DEVNOTE: *** HIGHLIGHTS_END ***]"
}